-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
-- ONE-TIME MANUAL BOOTSTRAP SCRIPT — this is NOT a Flyway migration and must
-- NEVER be placed in src/main/resources/db/migration/. Run it directly (psql)
-- against a target database exactly once, before Flyway ever runs against it.
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
--
-- Why this exists: V1 through V57 in db/migration assume a base schema that
-- was created via Hibernate `ddl-auto` in dev, never captured in Flyway (see
-- V1's own comment: "Some local/dev databases start empty and create the base
-- schema outside Flyway"). On a genuinely fresh database (a new Railway
-- Postgres instance), V2 fails immediately with `relation "vehicles" does not
-- exist`, and — because the full schema evolved a lot since V1 — patching every
-- later migration to tolerate a fresh DB would mean touching ~30 already-
-- numbered migration files. Instead: apply this script once to create the
-- complete current schema directly, then tell Flyway (via
-- spring.flyway.baseline-version=57) to treat the database as already being at
-- V57 — so it never replays V1-V57 at all, and only applies V58+ from here on.
--
-- Contents: generated by running the real application with
-- spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=create against a disposable, empty scratch
-- database (never against dev/prod data) and dumping the resulting schema with
-- `pg_dump --schema-only`, then mechanically making every statement idempotent
-- (safe to re-run / safe if some objects already exist):
--   - CREATE TABLE / CREATE SEQUENCE / CREATE INDEX -> added IF NOT EXISTS
--     (all natively supported by Postgres).
--   - ALTER TABLE ... ADD CONSTRAINT (primary keys, unique, foreign keys) ->
--     Postgres has no IF NOT EXISTS for this, so each is wrapped in
--     `DO $$ BEGIN ... EXCEPTION WHEN duplicate_object OR duplicate_table
--     OR invalid_table_definition THEN NULL; END $$;` — the three distinct
--     SQLSTATEs Postgres raises for "already exists" on a FK/CHECK (42710),
--     a UNIQUE constraint's backing index (42P07), and a second PRIMARY KEY
--     on the same table (42P16), respectively.
--
-- How to apply to Railway:
--   psql "$RAILWAY_DATABASE_URL" -f server/scripts/bootstrap/baseline-core-schema.sql
-- Then set SPRING_FLYWAY_BASELINE_VERSION=57 (or confirm application.yml's
-- default) on Railway and redeploy — Flyway will auto-baseline at V57 on next
-- startup (baseline-on-migrate is already true) since it'll see a non-empty
-- schema with no flyway_schema_history table yet.

SET statement_timeout = 0;
SET lock_timeout = 0;
SET idle_in_transaction_session_timeout = 0;
SET client_encoding = 'UTF8';
SET standard_conforming_strings = on;
SET check_function_bodies = false;
SET xmloption = content;
SET client_min_messages = warning;
SET row_security = off;
SET default_tablespace = '';
SET default_table_access_method = heap;

